your reply emails look. As you recall: your
replies clearly arrived at the relay, but then
weren't forwarded back to the 'student'. I want
to test whether that ugly subject line gets changed
by your mail client, or what else is different in
emails from your mail client.

correct possible way, except for using the 'R'
you thought unjustly caused an accusation.
I have a theory for that too, which we might test
at the same time.

In your reply, can you give me a phone number
where I could reach you in case in need a few
shots in a row. And maybe times when that would
be convenient for you. I'll work on the response to
this one first, to milk it.

Subject: First of Five
Body:
Dear whatever, I will send five
message now. I found the problem we had.
The CS mail server is willing to process
messages with a FROM at ...@cs.stanford.edu,
but not at ...@stanford.edu. That's to avoid
mail server takeovers.

Do different things with these five. I added a
very short reason for any warning msgs
right in the subject line.

The relay now only decides that you accidentally
signed if it literally finds "Best, Lucas" in the msg.
It used to look for just Lucas. That seemed too
broad.

Andreas

Subject: Second of Five
Body:
You are wonderful, whoever you are.
Just wonderful. Can I trust you with a
secret?

Mystery Student.

Subject: Third of Five
Body:
You haven't replied to my request
for a re-test because my girlfriend
left me. We were together for two
months! I miss her so much.

Agrieved.

Subject: Forth of Five
Body:
Dear, dear Lucas,

I still haven't heard back about taking
a week off to make up with my boyfriend.
But it's all for the best: he is a jerk!!! I
can't believe I fell for him.

But you, you are a wonderful man. My
mother thinks so too. I sent her a picture
I took through your bedroom window the
other night. I watch you whenever I can
get away. You look so cute when you sleep.

Would *you* like to take a week off with
me?!!!!! Yosemite? Tahoe? Bahamas?!
Paris!!!!! Yes, Paris. Just let me know, and
I'll pass the good news on to my mother.

Susie.

Subject: Dark Thoughts Bad Consequences
Body:
Susie, the love of my life told me you are
running away with her to Paris. I want to
warn you against such a move! I can get
very, very nasty. In my country, when your
fiance is taken from you, the robber's whole
family is eradicated.

Can you let me know how I am doing in
Stats60? I enjoy the course very much. It

to be in error. In fact: Best, Lucas in this
paragraph should now be OK.

We'll need a couple of back and forths for the
relay to see its own sig. Just reply to this, and
I'll reply to that reply.

Note: you'll need to guess even on replies.

BTW: earlier I opened one of the test messages
with 'Dear, dear Lucas'. You correctly commented that
this heading was a give-away. Nothing we can do about
that. This line was entered in the msg body by the 'student',
not the relay. I could eradicate your name from every msg,
but that wouldn't help, b/c you'd see that the resulting
sentence was damaged.

Let's not worry about that case.

Andreas

Body:
R

Hi Sarah,


Thanks for your email, let's see if this helps:


First, when we talk about getting "exactly a certain number of outcomes", w=
e seem to be asking a question about the sum of draws. Since the central li=
mit theorem applies to the sum of draws, we can approximate the distributio=
n of the sum of draws by a normal distribution. Since the normal distributi=
on is continuous, and thus puts zero probability on any single exact outcom=
e, we must use a further approximation to find the the probability of exact=
ly a certain number of outcomes. This last approximation uses the 0.5 rule-=
-that is, if the number of interest is N, then you would compute the probab=
ility under the normal curve of getting less than N+0.5, and subtract the p=
robability under the normal curve of getting less than N-0.5.


I hope that answers your question!

________________________________

Hope that helps!

Body:
H

Hi Alexis,


Your answer is incorrect, but you've made a very legitimate and common mist=
ake--you forgot to use the 0.5 rule. Note that the question is asking for t=
he probability of "fewer than 90  3's", which is the same as "fewer than or=
 equal to 89  3's", since you can't have a decimal number of 3's. However, =
in the normal approximation, you can have a decimal outcome, so we need to =
be careful, and the correction learned in class is to use 89.5 instead of 9=
0 in the computation--in some sense splitting the difference.


Hope that helps, and that you didn't waste too much time rechecking your an=
swer (your answer would be correct if it weren't for the 0.5 correction).

formula and was hoping you could possibly point me in the right direction?

Thank you so much for your help!

Sincerely,
Angela

Hi Angela,


For 4 A and B, you're doing the problem correctly, it's just a rounding err=
or (this problem has a somewhat unusually narrow allowable range). In gener=
al, for intermediate calculations, it is good to always keep 3 significant =
digits (which would give -0.0526) or 3 decimal places (which you did), whic=
hever gives higher precision.


For 5 A, note that getting "exactly 17 heads" is the same as getting "at le=
ast 17 heads" and (NOT "at least 18 heads")--both of which look like things=
 discussed in class.

Subject: Homework Question
Body:
Hi Lucas,

I have a question on Question 7c of the homework, which asks how many =
people we=E2=80=99d need to include in our SRS in order for the 95% =
confidence interval to have a margin of error or + or - 1%.

First, I determined that:

(1.96) * (100) * sqrt [p * (1-p)] / sqrt [n] =3D 1

Therefore, if we bring the constants over to the right side of the =
equation, we get:

sqrt [p * (1-p)] / sqrt [n] =3D .0051

Then, we square both sides to get:

[p * (1-p)] / n =3D 2.603 * 10^-5

We know that p is .71, so [p * (1-p)] =3D [.71 * .29] =3D .2059.

.2059 / n =3D 2.603 * 10^-5

.2059 =3D 2.603 * 10^-5 * n

n =3D 7909.8544


Therefore, I concluded that we=E2=80=99d need to sample 7910 in order to =
have a + or - 1% margin of error. I=E2=80=99ve tried plugging this =
answer into the homework site, but it says that this is the wrong =
answer. Could you please explain what I=E2=80=99m doing wrong?

Thanks so much!

Christian=

people we=E2=80=99d need to include in our SRS in order for the 95% confide=
nce
interval to have a margin of error or + or - 1%.

First, I determined that:

(1.96) * (100) * sqrt [p * (1-p)] / sqrt [n] =3D 1

Therefore, if we bring the constants over to the right side of the
equation, we get:

sqrt [p * (1-p)] / sqrt [n] =3D .0051

Then, we square both sides to get:

[p * (1-p)] / n =3D 2.603 * 10^-5

We know that p is .71, so [p * (1-p)] =3D [.71 * .29] =3D .2059.

.2059 / n =3D 2.603 * 10^-5

.2059 =3D 2.603 * 10^-5 * n

n =3D 7909.8544


Therefore, I concluded that we=E2=80=99d need to sample 7910 in order to ha=
ve a +
or - 1% margin of error. I=E2=80=99ve tried plugging this answer into the h=
omework
site, but it says that this is the wrong answer. Could you please explain
what I=E2=80=99m doing wrong?
-Aashna Garg

Subject: Question 3 on pset
Body:
Hi Lucas,

I am having some trouble with question 3e. I created a box model with
10,000 (1's) and 40,000 (0)'s. The SD of the box = (1-0) sqrt
((1/5)*(4/5))=.4. The Average is .2, the EV=900 (# of draws)*.2=180. The
SE=sqrt(900)*.4=12. Then I went on to calculate the chance that of a
success (drawing a ticket with a 1) occurred between 19-20% of the time.
Using the .5 rule, I calculated that 18.5% of 900 was 166.5 and 21.5% of
900 was 193.5. I calculated the z score for each of these number of tickets
using the EV and the SE and found that the z score was -1.125 and 1.125. I
think found that the area between those z scores was 75%. I inputed .75 as
my answer. Where am I going wrong?

Thank you very much!
Pascale

of that box?

Thank you!

Hi TA,

I have a question on Question 7c of the homework, which asks how many peopl=
e we'd need to include in our SRS in order for the 95% confidence interval =
to have a margin of error or + or - 1%.

First, I determined that:

(1.96) * (100) * sqrt [p * (1-p)] / sqrt [n] =3D 1

Therefore, if we bring the constants over to the right side of the equation=
, we get:

sqrt [p * (1-p)] / sqrt [n] =3D .0051

Then, we square both sides to get:

[p * (1-p)] / n =3D 2.603 * 10^-5

We know that p is .71, so [p * (1-p)] =3D [.71 * .29] =3D .2059.

.2059 / n =3D 2.603 * 10^-5

.2059 =3D 2.603 * 10^-5 * n

n =3D 7909.8544


Therefore, I concluded that we'd need to sample 7910 in order to have a + o=
r - 1% margin of error. I've tried plugging this answer into the homework s=
ite, but it says that this is the wrong answer. Could you please explain wh=
at I'm doing wrong?
-Aashna Garg

Hi TA,

I have a question on Question 7c of the homework, which asks how many peopl=
e we'd need to include in our SRS in order for the 95% confidence interval =
to have a margin of error or + or - 1%.

First, I determined that:

(1.96) * (100) * sqrt [p * (1-p)] / sqrt [n] =3D 1

Therefore, if we bring the constants over to the right side of the equation=
, we get:

sqrt [p * (1-p)] / sqrt [n] =3D .0051

Then, we square both sides to get:

[p * (1-p)] / n =3D 2.603 * 10^-5

We know that p is .71, so [p * (1-p)] =3D [.71 * .29] =3D .2059.

.2059 / n =3D 2.603 * 10^-5

.2059 =3D 2.603 * 10^-5 * n

n =3D 7909.8544


Therefore, I concluded that we'd need to sample 7910 in order to have a + o=
r - 1% margin of error. I've tried plugging this answer into the homework s=
ite, but it says that this is the wrong answer. Could you please explain wh=
at I'm doing wrong?
-Aashna Garg

Hi roboTA,

I have a question on Question 7c of the homework, which asks how many
people we=E2=80=99d need to include in our SRS in order for the 95% confide=
nce
interval to have a margin of error or + or - 1%.

First, I determined that:

(1.96) * (100) * sqrt [p * (1-p)] / sqrt [n] =3D 1

Therefore, if we bring the constants over to the right side of the
equation, we get:

sqrt [p * (1-p)] / sqrt [n] =3D .0051

Then, we square both sides to get:

[p * (1-p)] / n =3D 2.603 * 10^-5

We know that p is .71, so [p * (1-p)] =3D [.71 * .29] =3D .2059.

.2059 / n =3D 2.603 * 10^-5

.2059 =3D 2.603 * 10^-5 * n

n =3D 7909.8544


Therefore, I concluded that we=E2=80=99d need to sample 7910 in order to ha=
ve a +
or - 1% margin of error. I=E2=80=99ve tried plugging this answer into the h=
omework
site, but it says that this is the wrong answer. Could you please explain
what I=E2=80=99m doing wrong?


-Aashna Garg

Subject: Stats 60 Clarification
Body:
Dear Lukas,

Hope you're doing well. I had a question regarding the 0.5 rule when using
normal approximation. I was aware that during the homework, many questions
didn't use the 0.5 rule when approximating the area between two percentages
(for example, a 19-21% interval becomes an 18.5-21.5% interval). Are we
supposed to use it (because I thought we were supposed to in all
circumstances)?

Thanks,

Alexis

-- 
*Alexis Rochat*
B.A. Candidate History
B.A. Candidate International Relations
Class of 2019
Stanford University
